%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20very%20far%20away%20from%20Earth.%20Of%20course%2C%20it%20is%20true%20that%20the%20farther%20away%20a%20star%20is%2C%20the%20less%20bright%20it%20looks%20%E2%80%93%20a%20star%2010%20times%20farther%20away%20looks%20100%20times%20dimmer.%20But%20it%20turns%20out%20this%20isn't%20the%20whole%20answer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EImagine%20a%20bubble%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EPretend%2C%20for%20a%20moment%2C%20that%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ftimeline-of-the-universe-from-birth-to-death-2016-7%23%3A~%3Atext%3DThe%2520universe%2520has%2520been%2520around%2520for%2520about%252013.8%2520billion%2520years.%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Euniverse%20is%20so%20old%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20the%20light%20from%20even%20the%20farthest%20stars%20has%20had%20time%20to%20reach%20Earth.%20In%20this%20imaginary%20scenario%2C%20all%20of%20the%20stars%20in%20the%20universe%20are%20not%20moving%20at%20all.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPicture%20a%20large%20bubble%20with%20Earth%20at%20the%20center.%20If%20the%20bubble%20were%20about%2010%20light-years%20across%2C%20it%20would%20contain%20about%20a%20dozen%20stars.%20Of%20course%2C%20at%20several%20light%20years%20away%2C%20many%20of%20those%20stars%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fdarkest-skies-by-state-watch-space-events-stargazing%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ewould%20look%20pretty%20dim%20from%20Earth%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20keep%20enlarging%20the%20bubble%20to%201%2C000%20light-years%20across%2C%20then%20to%201%20million%20light%20years%2C%20and%20then%201%20billion%20light%20years%2C%20the%20farthest%20stars%20in%20the%20bubble%20will%20look%20even%20more%20faint.%20But%20there%20would%20also%20be%20more%20and%20more%20stars%20inside%20the%20bigger%20and%20bigger%20bubble%2C%20all%20of%20them%20contributing%20light.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20though%20the%20farthest%20stars%20look%20dimmer%20and%20dimmer%2C%20there%20would%20be%20a%20lot%20more%20of%20them%2C%20and%20the%20whole%20night%20sky%20should%20look%20very%20bright.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20seems%20I'm%20back%20where%20I%20started%2C%20but%20I'm%20actually%20a%20little%20closer%20to%20the%20answer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EAge%20matters%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20imaginary%20bubble%20illustration%2C%20I%20asked%20you%20to%20imagine%20that%20the%20stars%20are%20not%20moving%20and%20that%20the%20universe%20is%20very%20old.%20But%20the%20universe%20is%20only%20about%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhubble-deep-field-age-of-the-universe-2014-12%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E13%20billion%20years%20old%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20though%20that's%20an%20amazingly%20long%20time%20in%20human%20terms%2C%20it's%20short%20in%20astronomical%20terms.%20It's%20short%20enough%20that%20the%20light%20from%20stars%20more%20distant%20than%20about%2013%20billion%20light%20years%20hasn't%20actually%20reached%20Earth%20yet.%20And%20so%20the%20actual%20bubble%20around%20Earth%20that%20contains%20all%20the%20stars%20we%20can%20see%20only%20extends%20out%20to%20about%2013%20billion%20light-years%20from%20Earth.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20just%20are%20not%20enough%20stars%20in%20the%20bubble%20to%20fill%20every%20line%20of%20sight.%20Of%20course%2C%20if%20you%20look%20in%20some%20directions%20in%20the%20sky%2C%20you%20can%20see%20stars.%20If%20you%20look%20at%20other%20bits%20of%20the%20sky%2C%20you%20can't%20see%20any%20stars.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20that's%20because%2C%20in%20those%20dark%20spots%2C%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwebbs-pillars-creation-snap-shows-glittering-view-hubble-cant-see-2022-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Estars%20that%20could%20block%20your%20line%20of%20sight%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20so%20far%20away%20their%20light%20hasn't%20reached%20Earth%20yet.%20As%20time%20passes%2C%20light%20from%20these%20more%20and%20more%20distant%20stars%20will%20have%20time%20to%20reach%20us.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20Doppler%20shift%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EYou%20might%20ask%20whether%20the%20night%20sky%20will%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhow-universe-will-die-2017-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eeventually%20light%20up%20completely%3C%2Fa%3E.%20But%20that%20brings%20me%20back%20to%20the%20other%20thing%20I%20told%20you%20to%20imagine%3A%20that%20all%20of%20the%20stars%20are%20not%20moving.%20The%20universe%20is%20actually%20expanding%2C%20with%20the%20most%20distant%20galaxies%20moving%20away%20from%20Earth%20at%20nearly%20the%20speed%20of%20light.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBecause%20the%20galaxies%20are%20moving%20away%20so%20fast%2C%20the%20light%20from%20their%20stars%20is%20pushed%20into%20colors%20the%20human%20eye%20can't%20see.%20This%20effect%20is%20called%20the%20Doppler%20shift.%20So%2C%20even%20if%20it%20had%20enough%20time%20to%20reach%20you%2C%20you%20still%20couldn't%20see%20the%20light%20from%20the%20most%20distant%20stars%20with%20your%20eyes.%20And%20the%20night%20sky%20would%20not%20be%20completely%20lit%20up.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20allowfullscreen%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2FikgRZt1BSyk%3Fsi%3DhI249rH3IpNnH_De%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22560%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22YouTube%20video%20player%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22315%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20wait%20even%20longer%2C%20eventually%20the%20stars%20will%20all%20burn%20out%20%E2%80%94%20stars%20like%20the%20sun%20last%20only%20about%2010%20billion%20years.%20Astronomers%20hypothesize%20that%20in%20the%20distant%20future%20%E2%80%94%20a%20thousand%20trillion%20years%20from%20now%20%E2%80%94%20the%20universe%20will%20go%20dark%2C%20inhabited%20by%20only%20stellar%20remnants%20like%20white%20dwarfs%20and%20black%20holes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20though%20our%20night%20sky%20isn't%20completely%20filled%20with%20stars%2C%20we%20live%20in%20a%20very%20special%20time%20in%20the%20universe's%20life%2C%20when%20we're%20lucky%20enough%20to%20enjoy%20a%20rich%20and%20complex%20night%20sky%2C%20filled%20with%20light%20and%20dark.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EBrian%20Jackson%20is%20an%20associate%20professor%20of%20astronomy%20at%20Boise%20State%20University.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20article%20is%20republished%20from%20%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EThe%20Conversation%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E%20under%20a%20Creative%20Commons%20license.%20Read%20the%20%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fwhy-is-space-so-dark-even-though-the-universe-is-filled-with-stars-205810%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3Eoriginal%20article%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Folbers-paradox-why-space-dark-if-contains-billion-trillion-stars-2023-12%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1703958421000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65539feb58cf5fbccb962a55%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Folbers-paradox-why-space-dark-if-contains-billion-trillion-stars-2023-12%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%20universe%20should%20be%20a%20bright%20beacon%20of%20light%20from%20all%20the%20stars%20within%20it%2C%20but%20it's%20not.%20An%20astronomer%20explains%20the%20fascinating%20reasons%20why.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22insider%40insider.com%20(Brian%20Jackson)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A75%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Folbers-paradox-why-space-dark-if-contains-billion-trillion-stars-2023-12%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%